         <abstract>
            <p>An investor can always reduce portfolio variance and increase expected return by selling short individual assets. For example, an investor who is unable to forecast the performance of an industry, but able to anticipate the relative performance of individual companies, can use a hedged position within that industry to improve his portfolio performance. When the correlation between the hedged assets is imperfect, however, he will need a detailed understanding of portfolio theory: Faulty hedging can lead to instant disaster.</p>
          </abstract>
